questionTemplates.text:
M: When will the bank open?
W: It opens from 8:30 a.m. to 6:30 p.m. from Monday to Friday, and opens from 9:30 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. on Saturday and Sunday.
{a}

F: The blue shoes are so nice, but expensive.
M: But not as much as the black ones.
{a}

F: I always go to bed at 11.
M: Me too.
{a}

M: Can you believe I had to pay $ 30 for a haircut at Sadermale.
W: You should try the place where I go. It's only 15, but it takes a while to get an appointment.
{a}

M: How are you getting to the airport?
W: Well, I haven't really got any choice--I have to take the bus. My car is at the garage getting repaired, and a taxi is just too expensive.
{a}

W: What is the ticket price for the play?
M: 8 dollars. But two dollars for children, six or under. And with the student card, you pay four dollars fifty Cents.
{a}

W: What's ten plus five? Who knows? Hands up.
M: It's fifteen.
{a}

M: Could you help me translate the article into French?
W: Sorry, I'm busy now. Shall I do it tomorrow?
{a}

M: It's so hot here. Do you mind my opening the door?
F: Go ahead.
{a}

W: We ought to stop buying this kind of coffee. It always tastes terrible.
M: Maybe we shall get a new coffee machine instead.
{a}

M: Hi, Jenny. You look so angry! What's the matter?
W: My friend made a promise. He said he would pay for the broken ball. But he hasn't yet.
{a}

M: Professor Johnson, last night when I was putting the finishing touches on my paper, a computer failure completely wiped out my files, do you think I can have another day to retype it?
W: I'm sorry, Rod. I'm leaving for a conference tomorrow and I'll be away two weeks. I suppose you could send me an E-copy.
{a}

M: Have you tried Mary's cake?
W: I got the last piece and it was really wonderful.
{a}

W: I'll have the steak, French fries, and let's see, chocolate ice cream for dissert.
M: Oh, oh, you know these things will ruin your health, too much fat and sugar, how about ordering some vegetables and fruit instead?
{a}

M: Excuse me, Madam. Could I leave this here for a few hours, please?
W: Why not go to the luggage office over there?
{a}

W: What an accident! If you've been careful, things would not be as they are.
M: What do you mean? It was my fault? If it were, surely I'll take all responsibility for it.
{a}

M: Has mother bought the tickets for us yet?
F: No, she hasn't. She was too busy.
{a}

M: What time is our flight? Is it the 11:30 flight?
W: Yes. But we've got to leave two hours earlier. It's a long drive to the airport.
{a}

W: Hi, John. I haven't seen you for a few weeks.
M: Hi, Mary. I've been studying a lot for my final exam.
{a}

M: This is a one-way street. Didn't you see the sign?
W: Sorry. I didn't.
{a}

F: What would you like, a cup of tea or a cup of coffee?
M: Neither, thanks. A glass of water will be OK.
{a}

W: Good morning, Mr. Li. Did you sleep well last night after your long flight?
M: Good morning. Yes, I did. I feel totally rested and I'm now ready for our meeting.
{a}

M: I hear Mary isn't getting much support in her running against Steve in the election.
W: It is not over yet. I think she will make a come-back next time.
{a}

M: You were seen hanging about the store on the night when it was robbed, weren't you?
W: Me? You must have made a mistake. I was at home that night.
{a}
